          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient loses taste sensation over the anterior two-thirds of the tongue but retains general sensation in the same area. Which nerve is most likely damaged?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lingual nerve (branch of CN V₃)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lingual nerve carries general sensation (touch, pain, temperature) from the anterior two-thirds. If it were damaged, general sensation would also be lost, which is not the case here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Chorda tympani (branch of CN VII)</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The chorda tympani carries taste fibres from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue. It travels alongside the lingual nerve but can be damaged independently, such as during middle ear surgery.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>CN IX supplies both general sensation and taste to the posterior one-third of the tongue, not the anterior two-thirds.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hypoglossal nerve (CN XII)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>CN XII is a purely motor nerve supplying the tongue muscles. Its damage causes tongue deviation on protrusion, not sensory or taste loss.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the tongue innervation map: general sensation to the anterior two-thirds comes from the lingual nerve (V₃), taste from the chorda tympani (VII), and both modalities for the posterior one-third from CN IX."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The anterior two-thirds of the tongue has dual innervation: the lingual nerve (V₃) for general sensation and the chorda tympani (VII) for taste, which is why isolated taste loss points to chorda tympani injury."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
