          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>If the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) is injured, which specific pharyngeal func</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>If the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) is injured, which specific pharyngeal function would be impaired due to loss of its motor component?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Constriction of the pharynx by the superior constrictor</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>All three pharyngeal constrictors receive motor supply from CN X via the pharyngeal plexus, not from CN IX.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Elevation of the pharynx by the stylopharyngeus muscle</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Stylopharyngeus is the only pharyngeal muscle supplied by CN IX. It is one of three longitudinal muscles that elevate the pharynx during swallowing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Opening of the Eustachian tube by salpingopharyngeus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Salpingopharyngeus is innervated by CN X via the pharyngeal plexus, not by CN IX. It would be unaffected by a glossopharyngeal nerve lesion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Tension of the soft palate by tensor veli palatini</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Tensor veli palatini is innervated by the mandibular division of CN V (V₃), not by CN IX. It is the other exception to the CN X rule, but takes a different nerve.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key rule: the pharyngeal plexus (CN X) supplies all pharyngeal muscles except stylopharyngeus (CN IX) and tensor veli palatini (CN V₃). Stylopharyngeus is the only one innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Almost all pharyngeal muscles are CN X, with just two exceptions — stylopharyngeus (CN IX) and tensor veli palatini (CN V₃)."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
