          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A 70-year-old man presents with regurgitation of undigested food hours after eat</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A 70-year-old man presents with regurgitation of undigested food hours after eating and persistent halitosis. Endoscopy reveals a posterior pharyngeal pouch. Through which anatomical weak point did this diverticulum most likely herniate?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Gap between the superior and middle pharyngeal constrictors</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This gap transmits the stylopharyngeus muscle and the glossopharyngeal nerve. It is not the site of pharyngeal pouch formation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Gap between the middle and inferior pharyngeal constrictors</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The internal laryngeal nerve and superior laryngeal vessels pass through this gap. Zenker's diverticulum does not form here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Killian's dehiscence, between the thyropharyngeus and cricopharyngeus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Killian's dehiscence is a triangular gap between the oblique fibres of thyropharyngeus and the horizontal fibres of cricopharyngeus (both parts of the inferior constrictor). Raised intrapharyngeal pressure forces mucosa through this unsupported area, forming a pulsion diverticulum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Through the pharyngobasilar fascia above the superior constrictor</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The pharyngobasilar fascia is thickest superiorly and compensates for the absence of muscle reinforcement in that region. Zenker's diverticulum forms much lower, at the junction of the two parts of the inferior constrictor.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: Killian's dehiscence lies between the two parts of the inferior constrictor — thyropharyngeus (oblique) above and cricopharyngeus (horizontal) below. This is where Zenker's diverticulum herniates posteriorly."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Killian's dehiscence is a classic example of how differences in muscle fibre orientation create a structural weakness — the oblique thyropharyngeus and horizontal cricopharyngeus leave a triangular gap vulnerable to pulsion forces."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
